	<div id="editor-body" contenteditable="true" autocomplete="off" spellcheck="false"><h1><b>Did History Really Happen?</h1></b><figure class="image caption-enabled full"><div class="image-wrapper" contenteditable="false"><img src="/assets/images/sets/ex.jpeg" alt=""></div><figcaption contenteditable="true">Frederick Dielman, “History” (1896)</figcaption></figure><blockquote>This article is part of the Boundary Hunter column.</blockquote><p>The biggest revolution in the field of history, these last four decades, has been the recognition that traditional histories — historical narratives — are as much narrative as they are history, and that that distinction matters.</p><figure class="image"><div class="image-wrapper" contenteditable="false"><img src="/assets/images/sets/separator.png" alt=""></div><figcaption contenteditable="true"></figcaption></figure><p>We used to think the job of the historian was to excavate the past as one might the ground, in a very straightforward way revealing what was already there. But then somebody picked up the Roman Empire in one hand and a History of the Roman Empire in the other and noticed that only one of them had a clear beginning, middle, and end. When you are digging in the earth, no one ever announces “chapter two.”</p></div>

